WEBVTT

00:01.441 --> 00:04.576
I'm offering you a deal--
one for you, one for me.

00:04.578 --> 00:05.677
You are not getting my office.
Oh, yes, I am

00:05.679 --> 00:07.378
'cause she's gone, Harvey.

00:07.380 --> 00:08.613
It's time for you
to take the reins.

00:08.615 --> 00:10.315
I'm here to ask you out.

00:10.317 --> 00:11.749
As of this morning,
I'm the head of my firm,

00:11.751 --> 00:13.585
and, when I thought
of sharing that with someone,

00:13.587 --> 00:14.752
I thought of you.

00:14.754 --> 00:16.454
One dinner.

00:16.456 --> 00:17.488
I figured out what I want,
and I want to be

00:17.490 --> 00:18.957
a partner at this firm.

00:18.959 --> 00:20.291
All I'm asking is
for a seat at the table.

00:20.293 --> 00:22.260
I'll have Louis about it.

00:22.262 --> 00:24.462
You're afraid to take
responsibility for this firm,

00:24.464 --> 00:26.231
and you won't admit it
to yourself!

00:26.233 --> 00:27.599
You told me that you're
now head of the firm.

00:27.601 --> 00:29.267
I am--I just haven't
told Louis yet.

00:29.269 --> 00:30.568
I think this may have
been a mistake.

00:30.570 --> 00:31.636
You don't think
I've had fantasies

00:31.638 --> 00:32.704
that one day you'd take me

00:32.706 --> 00:34.572
in your arms and kiss me?

00:34.574 --> 00:36.474
Those fantasies weren't
of a man who's still too afraid

00:36.476 --> 00:38.476
to take control of a firm
that bears his name.

00:38.478 --> 00:39.811
I'm not giving up
my associates!

00:39.813 --> 00:41.512
That's enough.

00:41.514 --> 00:42.580
Donna asked for a seat
at the table,

00:42.582 --> 00:44.315
and I gave her one.

00:44.317 --> 00:45.617
You don't make her goddamn
senior partner.

00:45.619 --> 00:46.684
If Jessica were here,
she'd tell you to do

00:46.686 --> 00:48.019
the same exact thing.

00:48.021 --> 00:49.587
Jessica isn't here, but I am.

00:49.589 --> 00:51.556
I think I know
what you may need.

00:51.558 --> 00:53.558
If you're telling me that
I need to talk to Tara...

00:53.560 --> 00:55.026
You were gonna get married.

00:55.028 --> 00:58.263
That can't all end
over a voicemail.

00:58.265 --> 01:00.331
I know we haven't spoken.

01:00.333 --> 01:02.333
I just really need
to see you tonight.

01:02.335 --> 01:04.869
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:06.640 --> 01:09.641
<i>[smooth music]</i>

01:09.643 --> 01:16.748
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:23.356 --> 01:25.423
[giggles]

01:27.627 --> 01:30.461
Oh, wow,

01:30.463 --> 01:32.764
the sunrise is beautiful
from up here.

01:32.766 --> 01:35.033
To be honest, I can't remember
the last time

01:35.035 --> 01:38.369
I saw the sun rise.
Really?

01:38.371 --> 01:40.638
It takes something
pretty special

01:40.640 --> 01:43.775
to get me up before 7:00 a.m.

01:47.514 --> 01:51.382
As I recall,
I was pretty special last night.

01:51.384 --> 01:54.552
There--you surprised me again.

01:54.554 --> 01:56.321
You know, the truth is
I'm a little surprised

01:56.323 --> 01:58.890
by all this myself.
What do you mean?

01:58.892 --> 02:01.793
Well, I mean, you disappear
for nearly a year,

02:01.795 --> 02:05.530
and then, one day, you suddenly
show up in a '57 Chevy--

02:05.532 --> 02:08.399
'72 Ferrari, but, yeah.

02:08.401 --> 02:10.568
And you sweep me off my feet.

02:10.570 --> 02:12.804
And I liked it.

02:12.806 --> 02:15.340
That's good 'cause
I wasn't sure you would.

02:15.342 --> 02:19.911
Of course you weren't.
You don't really know me yet.

02:19.913 --> 02:23.348
Till yesterday, we'd spent
about 50 hours together,

02:23.350 --> 02:25.583
and we'd spent most of them
talking about you.

02:25.585 --> 02:27.819
I know, and that's what I love
about our relationship.

02:27.821 --> 02:31.889
[laughs]

02:31.891 --> 02:35.593
Harvey...
Paula...

02:35.595 --> 02:37.428
Before you say
what I think you're gonna say,

02:37.430 --> 02:42.700
let me say you may know me
better than anyone.

02:42.702 --> 02:45.503
And now I'd like
to get to know you too.

02:45.505 --> 02:46.904
I'd like that.

02:46.906 --> 02:54.379
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:55.482 --> 02:58.716
<i>I guess what I'm trying</i>
<i>to say is I acted irrationally,</i>

02:58.718 --> 03:04.522
but please, Tara, if you could
just give me another chance...

03:04.524 --> 03:09.927
I promise you that I will
never let you down again.

03:09.929 --> 03:11.963
You know you can't
say that, Louis.

03:11.965 --> 03:13.631
Wait, I'm sorry, what?
This is my role play.

03:13.633 --> 03:15.533
I can say whatever
the hell I want.

03:15.535 --> 03:17.502
And we've talked about you
making bold proclamations

03:17.504 --> 03:18.836
about your own behavior.

03:18.838 --> 03:20.638
What does that
have to do with this?

03:20.640 --> 03:22.874
You just promised to never
let Tara down again.

03:22.876 --> 03:24.742
That is unrealistic.

03:24.744 --> 03:26.878
What happens when you inevitably
break that promise?

03:26.880 --> 03:28.913
I'll apologize and promise
I'll never do it again.

03:28.915 --> 03:31.616
And you don't see a problem
with that pattern?

03:31.618 --> 03:33.951
What I see, Dr. Lipschitz,
is we're 46 minutes

03:33.953 --> 03:36.754
into this session, and I haven't
gotten closure yet.

03:36.756 --> 03:39.724
Louis, we spent seven years
on the fact that your mother

03:39.726 --> 03:42.693
made you wear
Esther's hand-me-ups.

03:42.695 --> 03:44.762
You're not getting closure
in 50 minutes.

03:44.764 --> 03:47.465
Well, then what the hell
am I paying you for?

03:48.535 --> 03:50.568
Okay, Louis.

03:51.738 --> 03:54.705
What's really going on here?

03:54.707 --> 03:57.575
It's not about Tara.

04:00.580 --> 04:02.847
It's--It's about the baby.

04:02.849 --> 04:04.816
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:04.818 --> 04:07.785
I'm just worried
I'll never be a father.

04:07.787 --> 04:11.589
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:11.591 --> 04:15.893
I think that's a good place
for us to pick up next week.

04:15.895 --> 04:17.628
- What the fu--?
- Louis, calm down.

04:17.630 --> 04:19.464
No, I just told you
my deepest fear

04:19.466 --> 04:20.665
is that my clock is running out,
and all you care about

04:20.666 --> 04:22.667
is your precious time?

04:22.669 --> 04:25.036
Has it ever occurred to you
that you don't have a clock

04:25.038 --> 04:27.672
and can have children
whenever you want?

04:27.674 --> 04:28.940
Well, that sounds like
a load of crap coming from a guy

04:28.942 --> 04:30.675
who's looking at his clock.

04:30.677 --> 04:33.544
What about your idol,
Tony Randall?

04:33.546 --> 04:36.881
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:36.883 --> 04:38.816
Oh, my God.

04:38.818 --> 04:41.752
Tony Randall fathered
his first child at 77.

04:41.754 --> 04:43.588
Doc, this is fantastic.

04:43.590 --> 04:45.056
So you're good till next week.

04:45.058 --> 04:46.624
What, are you nuts?
I'm teetering.

04:46.626 --> 04:48.693
Clear up tomorrow,
all afternoon.

04:48.695 --> 04:51.762
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:51.764 --> 04:53.264
I was at work.

04:53.266 --> 04:56.234
It was the kids'
daycare calling.

04:56.236 --> 04:57.902
Shannon never showed up.

04:57.904 --> 04:59.704
And then what happened?

04:59.706 --> 05:03.241
Then the police called.
My world ended.

05:03.243 --> 05:05.009
And one month later,
I got a letter

05:05.011 --> 05:07.578
from the insurance company
saying Shannon lied

05:07.580 --> 05:08.880
on her application.

05:08.882 --> 05:10.815
About what?

05:10.817 --> 05:12.984
They're claiming
she was a smoker.

05:12.986 --> 05:15.686
- Was she?
- No, she quit five years ago,

05:15.688 --> 05:17.622
and she was totally
up-front about it.

05:17.624 --> 05:21.025
So then why would they think
she lied on her application?

05:21.027 --> 05:24.729
Because of this.

05:24.731 --> 05:26.864
It's a picture of Shannon
at her cousin's wedding.

05:26.866 --> 05:29.033
They sent it to me
along with her denied claim.

05:29.035 --> 05:32.069
Please tell me this picture
is over five years old.

05:32.071 --> 05:34.739
It was taken eight months ago.

05:34.741 --> 05:36.007
They must've gone
into her Facebook page.

05:36.009 --> 05:37.842
Shit.

05:37.844 --> 05:39.744
It was one cigarette,
and I gave her hell for it.

05:39.746 --> 05:41.946
It doesn't matter
if it was one or a hundred,

05:41.948 --> 05:44.615
it's enough for them to claim
her policy is null and void.

05:44.617 --> 05:47.919
My wife died
in a car accident, Mr. Ross.

05:47.921 --> 05:50.087
She was a healthy
39-year-old woman.

05:50.089 --> 05:53.925
She died rushing from her job
to pick up our children.

05:53.927 --> 05:55.993
What the hell does any of this
have to do with smoking?

05:55.995 --> 05:58.696
It shouldn't have
anything to do with it,

05:58.698 --> 05:59.864
but this company is not
in the business

05:59.866 --> 06:01.098
of helping people.

06:01.100 --> 06:03.034
It's in the business
of making money.

06:03.036 --> 06:05.937
So if they can find any reason
not to honor a claim,

06:05.939 --> 06:09.073
they'll take it.

06:09.075 --> 06:13.644
Without that insurance money,
we're gonna lose our home.

06:13.646 --> 06:16.013
Please--my children
have lost enough.

06:16.015 --> 06:20.952
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:20.954 --> 06:23.020
I'll find a way.

06:24.791 --> 06:28.693
<i>♪ See the money,</i>
<i>wanna stay for your meal ♪</i>

06:28.695 --> 06:31.963
<i>♪ Get another piece of pie</i>
<i>for your wife ♪</i>

06:31.965 --> 06:35.099
<i>♪ Everybody wanna know</i>
<i>how it feel ♪</i>

06:35.101 --> 06:38.936
<i>♪ Everybody wanna see</i>
<i>what it's like ♪</i>

06:38.938 --> 06:41.839
<i>♪ I'll even eat a bean pie,</i>
<i>I don't mind ♪</i>

06:41.841 --> 06:45.810
<i>♪ Me and Missy is so busy,</i>
<i>busy making money ♪</i>

06:45.812 --> 06:47.678
<i>♪ All right ♪</i>

06:47.680 --> 06:48.750
<i>♪ All step back,</i>
<i>I'm 'bout to dance ♪</i>

06:48.751 --> 06:52.751
<b><font color="#00FF00">♪ Suits 7x02 ♪</font></b>
<font color="#00FFFF">The Statue</font>
