<font color="#00FFFF">@elder_man</font>

06:59.861 --> 07:02.461
Hey, I didn't know anybody
was moving in here.

07:02.463 --> 07:04.130
It looks great.

07:04.132 --> 07:05.731
Well, as it turns out,
we're getting ourselves

07:05.733 --> 07:08.134
a new partner, and they needed
a new office, so.

07:08.136 --> 07:09.869
New partner?
That's fantastic.

07:09.871 --> 07:11.537
Shows we're back on our feet.

07:11.539 --> 07:12.872
What firm are they from?

07:12.874 --> 07:15.474
- This one.
- I don't understand.

07:15.476 --> 07:17.143
That's 'cause it hasn't
been announced yet,

07:17.145 --> 07:19.478
but you're looking at
the newest senior partner

07:19.480 --> 07:20.913
at Pearson Specter Litt.

07:20.915 --> 07:24.150
Wow.
congratulations, Donna.

07:24.152 --> 07:27.153
You must be thrilled.
I am.

07:27.155 --> 07:28.687
And I know what
you're thinking--

07:28.689 --> 07:30.689
how can a secretary
be made a partner?

07:30.691 --> 07:32.725
But--
I wasn't thinking that, Donna.

07:32.727 --> 07:35.561
I know how hard you work and
how much you mean to this firm

07:35.563 --> 07:39.165
and everyone in it.
Thanks, Katrina.

07:39.167 --> 07:41.834
You're welcome.
I'll let you get back to work.

07:41.836 --> 07:46.772
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:46.774 --> 07:49.175
All I'm saying is
I think you're rushing it.

07:49.177 --> 07:51.744
And I'm saying that,
when you overthrow a dictator,

07:51.746 --> 07:53.812
you don't leave their statue
up in the square.

07:53.814 --> 07:55.648
You tear it the hell down.

07:55.650 --> 07:57.750
You don't think that
this sends a message

07:57.752 --> 07:59.552
that you have
something to prove?

07:59.554 --> 08:03.289
Harvey, do you remember
Arthur Reeves?

08:03.291 --> 08:05.591
You mean the guy
who played Superman?

08:05.593 --> 08:06.725
That was George Reeves.

08:06.727 --> 08:08.794
Arthur Reeves founded this firm.

08:08.796 --> 08:11.597
And when Gordon, Schimdt, and
Van Dyke ran him out of town,

08:11.599 --> 08:13.799
they didn't just tear
his name off the wall.

08:13.801 --> 08:15.801
They called his biggest client
and told them

08:15.803 --> 08:19.238
to pack up their shit
and find another firm.

08:19.240 --> 08:21.640
- What's your point?
- My point is they wanted

08:21.642 --> 08:24.543
the world to know there was
a new sheriff in town,

08:24.545 --> 08:26.245
and the message that sends
isn't that you have

08:26.247 --> 08:31.483
something to prove--
it's that you're in charge.

08:31.485 --> 08:33.619
And you're staying that way.

08:33.621 --> 08:40.726
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:42.000 --> 08:48.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

08:56.244 --> 08:59.278
Hope you don't mind I took
the liberty of hanging that.

08:59.280 --> 09:01.780
Let me guess--
it's your last official act

09:01.782 --> 09:03.549
as my secretary.

09:03.551 --> 09:04.917
I told you once before
I wouldn't leave you

09:04.919 --> 09:08.687
high and dry.
Thanks, Donna.

09:08.689 --> 09:10.990
You're welcome, Harvey.

09:10.992 --> 09:15.261
And speaking of not being
your secretary anymore...

09:17.698 --> 09:19.765
This is a press release
announcing your partnership.

09:19.767 --> 09:21.300
It's more than just
a press release.

09:21.302 --> 09:25.004
It's a statement to the world.

09:25.006 --> 09:28.841
I'll take a look at it later.

09:28.843 --> 09:30.676
Do you mean, like,
later this afternoon

09:30.678 --> 09:34.280
or later, like,
after you go see Dr. Agard?

09:34.282 --> 09:35.948
- What?
- Harvey, the last time

09:35.950 --> 09:37.950
I stopped being your secretary,
you started having

09:37.952 --> 09:39.852
panic attacks,
and I'm not saying

09:39.854 --> 09:41.553
that's gonna happen again,
but you just got a look

09:41.555 --> 09:42.721
on your face,
and I wanna make sure

09:42.723 --> 09:43.956
you're okay with all of this.

09:43.958 --> 09:45.691
I'm okay with it, Donna.

09:45.693 --> 09:47.559
I'll get you what you need
to issue that release,

09:47.561 --> 09:51.030
but, right now, I gotta make
a statement of my own.

09:51.032 --> 09:55.968
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:55.970 --> 09:57.836
What can I do for you,
Mr. Ross?

09:57.838 --> 09:59.938
Well, you can start by writing
a check to Harry Kirst.

09:59.940 --> 10:02.074
- You don't waste time, do you?
- No, I don't.

10:02.076 --> 10:05.377
So why don't you cut my client
a check for $300,000,

10:05.379 --> 10:08.747
and I'll withdraw this lawsuit
I haven't filed yet.

10:08.749 --> 10:11.083
Mr. Ross, I'm afraid
there's been

10:11.085 --> 10:13.686
a little misunderstanding here.
We're not looking to settle.

10:13.688 --> 10:15.354
Then why the hell did you
set this meeting?

10:15.356 --> 10:17.656
'Cause it's policy to meet
with our clients and try

10:17.658 --> 10:19.692
to resolve their issues.

10:19.694 --> 10:21.794
Okay, well, my client's issue
is you're not honoring his claim

10:21.796 --> 10:23.362
so he can't support
his children.

10:23.364 --> 10:24.697
Yes, and I'm very sorry
about that,

10:24.699 --> 10:26.632
but my hands are tied.

10:26.634 --> 10:28.634
[scoffs]

10:28.636 --> 10:30.336
I get it.

10:30.338 --> 10:32.104
Your policy is to give people
the runaround so they get

10:32.106 --> 10:33.939
demoralized and drop their case.

10:33.941 --> 10:36.008
No, Mr. Ross, our policy is
to follow the letter

10:36.010 --> 10:38.711
of our contracts, and,
if we let one person who lied

10:38.713 --> 10:40.346
on their application
get away with it,

10:40.348 --> 10:41.814
we wouldn't have
a business anymore.

10:41.816 --> 10:43.849
Look at me.

10:43.851 --> 10:45.718
I'm not some personal injury
lawyer, all right?

10:45.720 --> 10:46.885
I work at Pearson Specter Litt.

10:46.887 --> 10:48.854
I'm not gonna get worn down.

10:48.856 --> 10:51.924
So I suggest you just
cut me a check.

10:51.926 --> 10:53.759
Save yourself the trouble
of me wiping the floor

10:53.761 --> 10:56.895
with you in court.

10:56.897 --> 10:59.031
As I said, my hands are tied,
but it won't be me

10:59.033 --> 11:00.866
you'll be going up
against in court.

11:00.868 --> 11:02.901
It'll be our outside counsel,
Mr. Ackerman.

11:02.903 --> 11:05.371
And, from what I've seen,

11:05.373 --> 11:08.407
nobody wipes the floor
with Mr. Ackerman.

11:08.409 --> 11:13.912
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:13.914 --> 11:15.748
Nice office.

11:15.750 --> 11:17.449
Mine's better.

11:17.451 --> 11:18.984
Isn't that the same line
you used when you thought

11:18.986 --> 11:20.152
your Ferrari was better
than my Cobra?

11:20.154 --> 11:21.687
It was better.

11:21.689 --> 11:23.722
And a good line never gets old.

11:23.724 --> 11:27.960
- Tell that to your hairline.
- Tell that to your waistline.

11:27.962 --> 11:29.094
Good to see you, Harvey.

11:29.096 --> 11:30.896
What brings you down?

11:30.898 --> 11:32.064
I'm here to finish
a conversation

11:32.066 --> 11:34.133
we started years ago.

11:34.135 --> 11:36.034
Well, I know you're not
coming over here,

11:36.036 --> 11:37.703
so you must be talking about
me working over there.

11:37.705 --> 11:39.438
What if I am?

11:39.440 --> 11:40.973
I'd say "Which one of
my clients are you after?"

11:40.975 --> 11:42.875
because we both know
you can't have Pfizer.

11:42.877 --> 11:44.843
Yes, I can.

11:44.845 --> 11:46.445
Are you telling me
you're ready to drop

11:46.447 --> 11:48.147
Jessica's oldest client
just to get me?

11:48.149 --> 11:49.815
That's what I'm telling you.

11:49.817 --> 11:52.084
Ah.
Why now?

11:52.086 --> 11:55.187
Because Jessica's gone,
so now I can.

11:58.793 --> 12:01.427
- Then make me name partner.
- What?

12:01.429 --> 12:03.695
This isn't about Jessica's
gone so now you can--

12:03.697 --> 12:05.964
this is about Jessica's gone,
so now you wanna tell the world

12:05.966 --> 12:07.132
that you're not her.

12:07.134 --> 12:08.801
And that's not about hiring me.

12:08.803 --> 12:09.968
That's about getting my client.

12:09.970 --> 12:11.503
Alex, this is a win/win.

12:11.505 --> 12:12.971
I don't poach.
You come over.

12:12.973 --> 12:14.907
We have fun.
But I'm not gonna just

12:14.909 --> 12:16.875
give you the run of the place.
Then I'm not coming.

12:16.877 --> 12:18.444
Because my name is going up
on this wall within a year.

12:18.446 --> 12:19.945
And Pfizer's not leaving me.

12:19.947 --> 12:20.979
- Alex--
- You always say you're

12:20.981 --> 12:22.848
the better poker player.

12:22.850 --> 12:26.051
Well, not today, because I'm
all in, and you got nothing.

12:26.053 --> 12:29.021
So either add my name
to your letterhead

12:29.023 --> 12:30.756
or take your chips and go home.

12:30.758 --> 12:32.991
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:32.993 --> 12:35.227
Your Honor, they can dress
this up all they want,

12:35.229 --> 12:37.863
but the fact is the deceased
entered into a contract

12:37.865 --> 12:40.866
in bad faith by claiming
she was no longer a smoker.

12:40.868 --> 12:42.935
The only fact here is that
they're manufacturing

12:42.937 --> 12:45.003
a reason to weasel out
of a legitimate claim.

12:45.005 --> 12:46.939
Are you gonna tell the court
that we manufactured

12:46.941 --> 12:49.842
this picture of your client
smoking eight months ago?

12:49.844 --> 12:51.510
I'm well aware
of the photo that you sent

12:51.512 --> 12:53.879
a grieving husband,
but an image of a woman

12:53.881 --> 12:55.814
not inhaling a cigarette
doesn't prove anything.

12:55.816 --> 12:58.484
- She lied on her application.
- Which had nothing

12:58.486 --> 12:59.952
to do with how she died.

12:59.954 --> 13:01.253
And manner of death
isn't at issue here.

13:01.255 --> 13:03.489
The contract is.
He's got a point.

13:03.491 --> 13:05.123
Your Honor, they're claiming
that my client entered

13:05.125 --> 13:07.526
into a policy in bad faith.

13:07.528 --> 13:09.862
Well, what kind of faith is it
when a company pores through

13:09.864 --> 13:12.130
a woman's social media history
just to stick it

13:12.132 --> 13:14.132
to her grieving husband
and three children?

13:14.134 --> 13:16.168
Better faith than a man
that pretended to be an attorney

13:16.170 --> 13:18.070
for the better part
of three years.

13:18.072 --> 13:19.905
What are you talking about?

13:19.907 --> 13:23.242
Your Honor, this is Mr. Ross'
Harvard diploma.

13:23.244 --> 13:27.212
The only problem is Mr. Ross
never actually went to Harvard.

13:27.214 --> 13:31.049
The only place he did graduate
from was Danbury Federal Prison

13:31.051 --> 13:33.919
where he spent time
for impersonating a lawyer.

13:33.921 --> 13:36.154
All right, that is
inadmissible and irrelevant.

13:36.156 --> 13:39.091
You're claiming bad faith.
Your whole life is bad faith.

13:39.093 --> 13:40.859
I think a jury should have
a chance to hear that.

13:40.861 --> 13:42.861
- Your Honor, this--
- Your motion to dismiss

13:42.863 --> 13:47.566
is denied, Mr. Ackerman, but,
Mr. Ross, I am inclined to agree

13:47.568 --> 13:50.536
that your history is relevant
to this case, which means,

13:50.538 --> 13:54.006
if he wants to bring it up
at trial, I'm not stopping him.

13:57.212 --> 14:00.013
So that's how you're gonna
play it?

14:00.015 --> 14:01.548
- Excuse me?
- You're not gonna give me

14:01.550 --> 14:03.082
your real settlement offer
right now?

14:03.084 --> 14:04.951
I have no idea
what you're talking about.

14:04.953 --> 14:06.185
Bullshit--I knew there was
a reason that woman

14:06.187 --> 14:08.087
didn't give me an offer before.

14:08.089 --> 14:09.956
Now I know it's because
you wanted me to see that.

14:09.958 --> 14:11.658
Now that you mention it,
I did take the liberty

14:11.660 --> 14:13.660
of whipping up a little
standard boilerplate.

14:13.662 --> 14:15.228
No admission of guilt,
you settle for pennies

14:15.230 --> 14:16.996
on the dollar, and that's
take it or leave it.

14:16.998 --> 14:18.631
Well, then let me
tell you right now--

14:18.633 --> 14:20.300
we're leaving it.
You're required to present

14:20.302 --> 14:21.935
this to your client.
Well, I'm also required

14:21.937 --> 14:23.736
to give them my legal opinion,

14:23.738 --> 14:25.338
which is that you stand to lose
a lot more than that.

14:25.340 --> 14:27.340
Maybe you missed what
just went on back there.

14:27.342 --> 14:30.209
What went on back there
is the judge ruled in my favor,

14:30.211 --> 14:31.711
and you didn't get
your case dismissed.

14:31.713 --> 14:33.246
He also showed his hand.

14:33.248 --> 14:35.181
Now, how do you think
12 jurors are gonna rule

14:35.183 --> 14:37.717
when it's plain as day
that the guy hearing the case

14:37.719 --> 14:39.752
doesn't even trust you?

14:39.754 --> 14:47.026
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:49.965 --> 14:52.231
- Good, you're here.
- Of course we are.

14:52.233 --> 14:53.800
When the managing partner
calls a meeting,

14:53.802 --> 14:55.234
the rest of the partners
show up.

14:55.236 --> 14:57.136
So what'd you want
to talk about?

14:57.138 --> 14:59.372
I wanna talk about bringing on
Pfizer as a client.

14:59.374 --> 15:01.040
Harvey, I'm sure
you already know this--

15:01.042 --> 15:02.642
that would mean dropping
Jim Reynolds.

15:02.644 --> 15:03.776
I think that's the point,
and I think

15:03.778 --> 15:05.345
it's a great idea, Harvey.

15:05.347 --> 15:07.113
Pfizer's ten times the size
of Jim Reynolds,

15:07.115 --> 15:08.982
and Jessica's always
been stubborn about him.

15:08.984 --> 15:10.750
Good, because, in order
to do that, we need to make

15:10.752 --> 15:12.385
Alex Williams a name partner.

15:12.387 --> 15:14.220
- What?
- Who do you think's

15:14.222 --> 15:16.055
bringing Pfizer over here
in the first place?

15:16.057 --> 15:18.691
So then give him a corner
office with a killer view

15:18.693 --> 15:20.226
because I'm not gonna do
something like that

15:20.228 --> 15:21.761
for someone I barely know.
Harvey--

15:21.763 --> 15:23.396
Well, I've known him
for 15 years,

15:23.398 --> 15:24.731
and I'm vouching for him.
I don't care if you

15:24.733 --> 15:26.299
came out of the womb with him.

15:26.301 --> 15:28.001
You don't just slap
somebody's name on the wall

15:28.003 --> 15:29.402
to get a client.
I'm not just slapping

15:29.404 --> 15:31.204
his name up, Louis.
I'm making a move.

15:31.206 --> 15:33.039
- Harvey--
- Hey, that's enough.

15:33.041 --> 15:34.841
I asked you last night
if you had any problems

15:34.843 --> 15:36.809
with me calling the shots,
and you said you didn't.

15:36.811 --> 15:39.178
Now, are you on board
with this or not?

15:39.180 --> 15:41.214
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:41.216 --> 15:43.116
Okay, Harvey, I'm on board.

15:43.118 --> 15:49.856
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:49.858 --> 15:51.858
Ah, there you are.
I need your help.

15:51.860 --> 15:54.160
And you can have it
after I've enjoyed

15:54.162 --> 15:55.728
my ham sandwich in peace.

15:55.730 --> 15:57.363
Nope, sorry, that ham's
gonna have to wait.

15:57.365 --> 15:59.666
Harvey is about to make
some stranger name partner.

15:59.668 --> 16:01.367
What?
Louis, you must've

16:01.369 --> 16:04.270
misunderstood something.
Gretchen, I heard him

16:04.272 --> 16:06.072
clear as a frickin' bell.

16:06.074 --> 16:08.374
He wants one of the guy's
clients, name partnership

16:08.376 --> 16:10.443
is the price, and I think
it's a huge mistake.

16:10.445 --> 16:12.345
- Well, did you tell him that?
- Yes, of course,

16:12.347 --> 16:14.247
but he couldn't hear me.

16:14.249 --> 16:15.882
And I told him last night that
I would back his decisions.

16:15.884 --> 16:18.184
Which means you want me
to find out as much dirt

16:18.186 --> 16:20.319
as I can on the sucker
so you can convince Harvey

16:20.321 --> 16:22.188
not to hire him.

16:22.190 --> 16:23.790
Exactly, so let's move
this little piggy to the market

16:23.792 --> 16:25.324
and go--
Not gonna happen, Louis.

16:25.326 --> 16:27.193
Gretchen, did you not hear
what I just said?

16:27.195 --> 16:29.095
I heard you.
Have you never heard the saying

16:29.097 --> 16:30.697
"there's more than one way
to skin a cat"?

16:30.699 --> 16:32.799
- You mean "stuff a cat."
- Why would I mean

16:32.801 --> 16:34.467
"stuff a cat"?
Because they are

16:34.469 --> 16:36.803
glorious creatures, and only
a barbarian would skin one.

16:36.805 --> 16:39.439
Louis, your brain
is not right.

16:39.441 --> 16:43.242
My point is, if Harvey wants
this man's client,

16:43.244 --> 16:46.079
there has to be another way
to get them.

16:46.081 --> 16:48.748
Holy shit.
You're right.

16:48.750 --> 16:51.384
If I can get Pfizer, Harvey
doesn't even have to bring

16:51.386 --> 16:53.486
this clown to the firm at all.

16:53.488 --> 16:55.455
Strap in, Gretchen, because
we're about to get

16:55.457 --> 16:58.391
elbow-deep into stuffing
the shit out of this cat.

16:58.393 --> 16:59.926
And I'm out.

16:59.928 --> 17:04.130
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:04.132 --> 17:05.732
I don't understand.

17:05.733 --> 17:08.367
I mean, I get that
the offer is horrible,

17:08.368 --> 17:10.336
but if the judge is letting
this thing go to trial,

17:10.338 --> 17:15.273
he must think I have a case.
You do have a case, Harry.

17:15.276 --> 17:17.510
But the lawyer on the other side
of this thing has made it clear

17:17.512 --> 17:19.278
that he is willing
to pull out all of the stops,

17:19.280 --> 17:20.913
no matter how low.

17:20.915 --> 17:22.348
They already used the photo
of Shannon.

17:22.349 --> 17:25.785
What else do they have?

17:25.787 --> 17:28.320
- Me.
- What are you talking about?

17:28.323 --> 17:30.823
Look, I am a fully-licensed
member of the bar now,

17:30.825 --> 17:35.361
but, before I was, I--
I was practicing law

17:35.363 --> 17:36.963
without a license,
and I got caught.

17:36.965 --> 17:38.765
And you didn't think
I should know that?

17:38.767 --> 17:40.166
I didn't think that
it would be relevant.

17:40.168 --> 17:42.168
It sure as hell
seems relevant.

17:42.170 --> 17:43.836
They are just trying to
prejudice the jury against me--

17:43.838 --> 17:45.438
They're going to be prejudiced
against you--I'd be.

17:45.440 --> 17:47.140
I'm telling you that
I can still win this.

17:47.142 --> 17:49.242
Still win?
They're gonna make it seem like

17:49.244 --> 17:51.210
Shannon lied on purpose,
and then I went out

17:51.212 --> 17:53.546
and hired a liar to cover it up.

17:53.548 --> 17:58.184
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:58.186 --> 17:59.886
If you want someone else
to handle this,

17:59.888 --> 18:04.390
I...
completely understand.

18:04.392 --> 18:07.794
The only problem with that
is I went to 15 firms

18:07.796 --> 18:10.363
before I came to you,

18:10.365 --> 18:13.966
and none of them would take
my case because of that photo.

18:15.904 --> 18:18.504
You were my last hope,
Mr. Ross,

18:18.506 --> 18:20.907
and now you're telling me
we're gonna lose.

18:20.909 --> 18:24.310
No, Harry.

18:24.312 --> 18:28.881
I am promising you that I will
not cost you this case.

18:30.985 --> 18:33.019
Good, Donna, you're here.

18:33.021 --> 18:34.821
I'm gonna need someone to draw
up a contract for Alex, and--

18:34.823 --> 18:36.556
Harvey, I don't think
we should drop Jim Reynolds.

18:36.558 --> 18:38.591
- What?
- I understand what

18:38.593 --> 18:40.426
you're doing, but I think that
maybe you're rushing into it.

18:40.428 --> 18:43.563
I'm not rushing, Donna.
I'm being decisive.

18:43.565 --> 18:45.464
Then you need to tell Jessica
before you do it.

18:45.466 --> 18:47.466
Tell Jessica?

18:47.468 --> 18:50.469
I'm doing this to show people
that this is my firm now.

18:50.471 --> 18:52.605
Asking Mommy's permission
isn't part of the plan.

18:52.607 --> 18:54.440
Well, is it also
part of the plan

18:54.442 --> 18:56.342
that you signal to the rest
of our long-term clients

18:56.344 --> 18:58.010
that you'll just throw them over
for the next big thing?

18:58.012 --> 18:59.545
Where the hell
is this coming from?

18:59.547 --> 19:01.214
What do you mean "where is
this coming from?"

19:01.216 --> 19:03.049
You made me a partner.
I'm saying my piece.

19:03.051 --> 19:04.984
That's what the meeting
was for.

19:04.986 --> 19:07.553
Well, maybe you didn't notice,
but you and Louis were having

19:07.555 --> 19:09.455
a private meeting.
Well, you know what, Donna?

19:09.457 --> 19:11.457
You had the balls to ask
for a seat at the table.

19:11.459 --> 19:13.359
So the next time
you have something to say,

19:13.361 --> 19:16.095
have the balls to say it
at the goddamn meeting.

19:21.169 --> 19:23.035
[door shuts]

19:26.007 --> 19:27.640
- Hey.
- Hey.

19:27.642 --> 19:30.610
How'd it go in court?

19:30.612 --> 19:32.979
Not great.

19:32.981 --> 19:37.884
No, don't tell me the judge
agreed to dismiss the case.

19:37.886 --> 19:39.986
The lawyer on the other side
somehow got a copy

19:39.988 --> 19:42.188
of my fake diploma.
Mike, that's bullshit.

19:42.190 --> 19:44.190
Your history has nothing
to do with this case.

19:44.192 --> 19:47.159
I know that, but he got
the judge on his side,

19:47.161 --> 19:49.028
and he's gonna try and do
the same thing with the jury,

19:49.030 --> 19:51.130
and my own client
barely trusts me.

19:51.132 --> 19:54.133
Okay, what are you gonna do?

19:54.135 --> 19:59.038
I was wondering if you would
take over the case for me.

19:59.040 --> 20:02.208
If that's what you want,
then I would be honored to.

20:02.210 --> 20:06.012
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:06.014 --> 20:09.015
[phone buzzing]

20:09.017 --> 20:11.017
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:11.019 --> 20:12.952
Alex, I'm glad you called.

20:12.954 --> 20:14.453
We're still working out
the paperwork--

20:14.455 --> 20:16.255
If you're still working
on the paperwork,

20:16.257 --> 20:18.224
how come I just found out you're
trying to poach my client?

20:18.226 --> 20:20.259
- What?
- Don't bullshit me.

20:20.261 --> 20:22.528
Kevin Bauer told me that PSL
called to set an appointment,

20:22.530 --> 20:24.563
and it sure as hell wasn't
to tell my own client

20:24.565 --> 20:27.099
that I'm going to be
name partner at your firm.

20:27.101 --> 20:29.068
God damn it.

20:29.070 --> 20:30.569
<i>You're telling me you</i>
<i>had nothing to do with this?</i>

20:30.571 --> 20:32.171
That's exactly
what I'm telling you.

20:32.173 --> 20:33.472
Then get your shit together
and either

20:33.474 --> 20:35.441
make this thing happen or not

20:35.443 --> 20:37.176
<i>'cause I went out on a limb</i>
<i>for you once before.</i>

20:37.178 --> 20:39.045
I'm not about to let
the same thing happen again.

20:39.047 --> 20:43.683
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:43.685 --> 20:45.251
Did you set a meeting
with Pfizer?

20:45.253 --> 20:47.019
Harvey, you don't understand.

20:47.021 --> 20:48.988
What I understand
is you were on board

20:48.990 --> 20:51.057
with bringing Alex over,
and then you tried

20:51.059 --> 20:52.959
to poach his client.
It's not like that.

20:52.961 --> 20:54.727
I knew what you really wanted
was Pfizer, so I tried

20:54.729 --> 20:57.196
to make it happen.
No, Louis, what I really

20:57.198 --> 21:00.166
wanted was to bring over
my friend who I've known

21:00.168 --> 21:01.968
for the last 15 years.
Yeah?

21:01.970 --> 21:03.169
Well, what about what
this friend thinks?

21:03.171 --> 21:04.537
We already had
that discussion,

21:04.539 --> 21:06.539
and then you went
behind my back.

21:06.541 --> 21:09.041
Maybe because it was stupid
of you to offer your friend

21:09.043 --> 21:11.210
name partner in the first place.
Excuse me?

21:11.212 --> 21:14.313
What kind of genius negotiator
gives away the house

21:14.315 --> 21:15.614
from the start?
Louis--

21:15.616 --> 21:18.184
No, you want Pfizer?

21:18.186 --> 21:20.619
You go get Pfizer.
But don't you bring in

21:20.621 --> 21:22.755
some Johnny-come-lately
and water down the name

21:22.757 --> 21:24.323
of this firm.
You don't give a shit about

21:24.325 --> 21:26.092
watering down this firm.

21:26.094 --> 21:28.561
You're scared of watering down
your place in it.

21:28.563 --> 21:30.129
I'm not afraid
of a third-rate lawyer.

21:30.131 --> 21:32.598
Bullshit, you're afraid
and you're jealous.

21:32.600 --> 21:34.567
And this entire firm knows it.
Now there's no need

21:34.569 --> 21:36.502
to be jealous
because he's not coming here.

21:36.504 --> 21:38.771
- Yes, he is.
- Well, then why don't you

21:38.773 --> 21:40.639
try reading the by-laws?

21:40.641 --> 21:42.708
Because in order to make
someone name partner,

21:42.710 --> 21:46.245
you need my vote or Jessica's
vote, and if you think

21:46.247 --> 21:48.547
she is going to ditch her
oldest client to bring in

21:48.549 --> 21:51.784
someone she doesn't even know,
you're out of your goddamn mind.

21:51.786 --> 21:56.255
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:56.257 --> 21:59.258
- Harvey, do you have a minute?
- That's about all I have.

21:59.260 --> 22:02.561
Okay, I was wondering
if it would be okay

22:02.563 --> 22:05.531
if I took over
Mike's pro Bono case.

22:05.533 --> 22:08.200
- What?
- Something came up.

22:08.202 --> 22:10.636
He asked me if I could do it.
I--I wanted to get

22:10.638 --> 22:13.205
your permission first.
No.

22:13.207 --> 22:15.641
- Why not?
- Because I made a deal

22:15.643 --> 22:18.177
with Mike, not you.
Now, you wanna tell me

22:18.179 --> 22:20.746
what's really going on here?
Because Mike's not giving away

22:20.748 --> 22:24.050
his first case
unless he's in a coma.

22:24.052 --> 22:26.585
The lawyer on the other side
outed Mike as a fraud.

22:26.587 --> 22:28.154
- Meaning?
- He brought out Mike's

22:28.156 --> 22:29.789
Harvard diploma,
and he prejudiced the judge.

22:29.791 --> 22:31.724
So Mike thinks if he hands
the case over to you,

22:31.726 --> 22:33.292
he takes that weapon
out of their hands.

22:33.294 --> 22:35.127
- Yes.
- Well, now it's a definite no.

22:35.129 --> 22:36.762
Why does that make it
a definite no?

22:36.764 --> 22:38.764
- Because I said so.
- Harvey, can you at least

22:38.766 --> 22:40.566
talk to Mike?
No, I can't.

22:40.568 --> 22:42.168
- Why not?
- Because I got a plane

22:42.170 --> 22:43.369
to catch.

22:43.371 --> 22:46.238
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:46.240 --> 22:47.840
You wanted to talk to me?

22:47.842 --> 22:49.642
<i>What gave it away?</i>
<i>The nine texts</i>

22:49.644 --> 22:51.710
<i>or the 16 messages?</i>
I was on a plane.

22:51.712 --> 22:53.579
Yeah, well, I'm in your old
office wondering why you even

22:53.581 --> 22:54.847
gave it to me if you're not
gonna let me make

22:54.849 --> 22:56.849
simple personnel decisions.

22:56.851 --> 22:58.818
Mike, if you let this asshole
bully you, you're gonna be

22:58.820 --> 23:00.319
backing down
for the rest of your life.

23:00.321 --> 23:03.122
I'm not backing down.
I am buying time

23:03.124 --> 23:05.424
so that I can stop this bullshit
from ever happening again.

23:05.426 --> 23:08.327
You don't need time.
I have a way.

23:08.329 --> 23:10.629
Stop apologizing
and start intimidating.

23:10.631 --> 23:12.231
Well, that's a hell
of a slogan, Harvey,

23:12.233 --> 23:13.833
but what does it actually mean?

23:13.835 --> 23:16.302
It means you go out,
you find a reporter,

23:16.304 --> 23:17.803
<i>and you take control</i>
<i>of the narrative.</i>

23:17.805 --> 23:19.805
Instead of a lying fraud,
you're a hero

23:19.807 --> 23:22.608
fighting for redemption.
I don't have time to change

23:22.610 --> 23:25.678
my image.
Look, if I lose this case,

23:25.680 --> 23:27.713
the only article that's gonna
get written is that I never

23:27.715 --> 23:29.448
should have been able to
practice law in the first place.

23:29.450 --> 23:31.851
Yeah, well, if you can't
figure out a way to win

23:31.853 --> 23:33.752
without Rachel's help,
then maybe I shouldn't have

23:33.754 --> 23:35.654
<i>brought you back</i>
<i>in the first place</i>

23:35.656 --> 23:38.390
because I've had about enough
of having every employee

23:38.392 --> 23:41.694
I have question
every decision I make.

23:41.696 --> 23:47.766
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:47.768 --> 23:49.902
I thought we were gonna meet
at the restaurant.

23:49.904 --> 23:52.404
I got down here early.

23:52.406 --> 23:55.374
Manhattan doesn't have
views like this.

23:55.376 --> 23:58.277
Thanks for making the time
to see me, Jessica.

23:58.279 --> 24:01.247
I will always make time
to see you, Harvey.

24:01.249 --> 24:03.149
Especially after you've flown
all the way out here

24:03.151 --> 24:05.651
to put the screws to me.
Louis called you, didn't he?

24:05.653 --> 24:07.753
About an hour
after your plane took off.

24:07.755 --> 24:09.455
Then you've already heard
his side of the story--

24:09.457 --> 24:11.323
And I don't need
to hear yours.

24:11.325 --> 24:13.359
- Jessica--
- Harvey, I understand

24:13.361 --> 24:16.462
wanting to make a statement,
but, you rush into this,

24:16.464 --> 24:18.931
the only statement you're making
is that you're not ready.

24:18.933 --> 24:20.799
I can't believe this.

24:20.801 --> 24:23.435
My first act as managing
partner, and you're cutting

24:23.437 --> 24:26.205
my legs out from under me.
I'm not cutting anything out.

24:26.207 --> 24:28.440
I'm trying to help you.
You can't give out name partner

24:28.442 --> 24:30.509
like it's Halloween candy.

24:30.511 --> 24:33.179
That doesn't sound like help.
That sounds like I'm a child--

24:33.181 --> 24:35.848
Harvey, you do this,
what's gonna happen

24:35.850 --> 24:37.816
the next time you wanna
bring someone over?

24:37.818 --> 24:40.486
I'll tell you what happens--
you're going to get rolled

24:40.488 --> 24:42.488
because you haven't
thought this through.

24:42.490 --> 24:44.757
You know what I think?
I think this has nothing

24:44.759 --> 24:46.525
to do with my decision.

24:46.527 --> 24:48.961
You're pissed I'm dumping
your client for a better one.

24:48.963 --> 24:52.398
No, Harvey, that's something
you'd be pissed about because

24:52.400 --> 24:53.966
you've never been able
to look at the big picture.

24:53.968 --> 24:55.968
Well, how's this
for big picture?

24:55.970 --> 24:57.970
I think you want it both ways.
And what the hell is that

24:57.972 --> 25:00.272
supposed to mean?
It means you want to live here

25:00.274 --> 25:02.708
and keep your name on my wall
because you're not ready

25:02.710 --> 25:04.476
to let go of my firm.

25:04.478 --> 25:07.413
Well, if that's how you really
feel, then take my name

25:07.415 --> 25:10.216
off your goddamn wall,
and then you can do

25:10.218 --> 25:12.484
whatever the hell you want.

25:12.486 --> 25:18.290
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:22.830 --> 25:26.765
[phone buzzing]

25:29.270 --> 25:32.538
Hey, I hope you don't think
I forgot about our dinner.

25:32.540 --> 25:35.874
Yeah, I don't, but I'm afraid
I have to reschedule.

25:35.876 --> 25:38.677
Sure, any time is good for me.

25:38.679 --> 25:40.879
Thanks for being
understanding.

25:40.881 --> 25:43.415
And, for the record,
I was really looking forward

25:43.417 --> 25:45.551
to getting to know
each other better.

25:45.553 --> 25:48.354
So was I.

25:48.356 --> 25:50.789
But the truth is I guess
I'm glad we're rescheduling.

25:50.791 --> 25:52.691
I didn't want to end up
focusing on myself

25:52.693 --> 25:55.361
like I did the last time.

25:55.363 --> 25:56.695
Why, is something going on?

25:56.697 --> 25:58.464
It's not a big deal.

25:58.466 --> 26:00.399
<i>Harvey, you can talk</i>
<i>to me about it.</i>

26:00.401 --> 26:03.369
- But you said before--
- I know what I said before,

26:03.371 --> 26:05.437
but this is different.
<i>How?</i>

26:05.439 --> 26:08.374
Because you heard me,
and you respected my wishes,

26:08.376 --> 26:09.875
which means instead of me
listening to you

26:09.877 --> 26:11.644
as your therapist, you know,
I'll be listening to you

26:11.646 --> 26:15.648
as your...
Not therapist.

26:15.650 --> 26:18.450
- Yes.
<i>- Look at that,</i>

26:18.452 --> 26:21.620
even when we cancel, I feel like
I'm getting to know you better.

26:21.622 --> 26:24.490
Me too.

26:24.492 --> 26:26.959
So are you gonna tell me
what's going on?

26:26.961 --> 26:29.461
You know what?

26:29.463 --> 26:32.765
Now that I just talked to you,
I feel like I can

26:32.767 --> 26:37.403
<i>work it through myself.</i>
Good.

26:37.405 --> 26:38.737
Good night, Harvey.

26:38.739 --> 26:41.540
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:41.542 --> 26:42.941
- Hey.
- Hey.

26:42.943 --> 26:44.877
- You busy?
- You know I am, which means

26:44.879 --> 26:47.579
you wouldn't be here
if it wasn't important.

26:47.581 --> 26:49.982
You're right.
I talked to Harvey.

26:49.984 --> 26:54.486
- You changed his mind?
- No, no.

26:54.488 --> 26:57.489
He told me if I run from this,
I'll be running forever.

26:57.491 --> 27:00.459
Look, I hate to say it,
but he might have a point.

27:00.461 --> 27:03.362
- He does.
- So then why are you here?

27:03.364 --> 27:05.764
'Cause he got me thinking.
The woman I first met over there

27:05.766 --> 27:08.634
said they couldn't let people
like Harry and his wife get away

27:08.636 --> 27:10.569
with lying on their application
because they wouldn't have

27:10.571 --> 27:12.538
a business anymore.
Right, but they didn't

27:12.540 --> 27:15.441
lie on their application.
No, they didn't.

27:15.443 --> 27:17.509
But a company that
thinks like that...

27:17.511 --> 27:21.513
Might have a policy of trying
to not pay their claims at all.

27:21.515 --> 27:23.015
Exactly.

27:23.017 --> 27:25.517
So if we can prove that that's
the company's real policy,

27:25.519 --> 27:27.453
we got 'em.
But, right, Mike, we can

27:27.455 --> 27:29.521
get all the subpoenas
in the world, but they're never

27:29.523 --> 27:31.023
going to hand over
a smoking gun like that.

27:31.025 --> 27:33.692
No, they won't.

27:33.694 --> 27:35.527
But I think you know someone
who can get it for us

27:35.529 --> 27:37.730
without issuing
any subpoena at all.

27:37.732 --> 27:42.901
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:42.903 --> 27:45.904
Ms. Cromwell, remember me?

27:45.906 --> 27:49.041
Yes, unfortunately.
If you'll excuse me.

27:49.043 --> 27:51.877
We have a job
we'd like to offer you.

27:51.879 --> 27:54.546
- Not interested.
- You haven't even heard

27:54.548 --> 27:56.548
what it is.
I don't need to know

27:56.550 --> 27:59.551
what it is--I don't do business
with people I don't trust.

27:59.553 --> 28:01.687
- You're a corporate spy.
- Not anymore--

28:01.689 --> 28:03.622
'cause the last mystery man
she brought me said word

28:03.624 --> 28:05.791
wouldn't get out about
our little arrangement.

28:05.793 --> 28:08.794
Well, it did, so now I'm trying
to make it as a legitimate

28:08.796 --> 28:12.698
headhunter, which pays
about 10% of what I made before,

28:12.700 --> 28:14.066
so, if you'll excuse me,
I'm meeting with

28:14.068 --> 28:15.601
an actual client
in a few minutes.

28:15.603 --> 28:16.969
Ms. Cromwell, please.

28:16.971 --> 28:19.505
A mother of three was killed
in a car accident,

28:19.507 --> 28:21.039
and she was 39 years old.

28:21.041 --> 28:23.842
Now her husband can't
support his children because

28:23.844 --> 28:25.677
Acumen Insurance is trying
to scam him

28:25.679 --> 28:27.546
out of their claim.
What am I supposed to do

28:27.548 --> 28:28.914
about that?
This can't be the first time

28:28.916 --> 28:31.016
they've done this.
And we're betting that

28:31.018 --> 28:32.951
there isn't a major corporation
in this city

28:32.953 --> 28:36.555
that you don't have access to.
Please.

28:36.557 --> 28:38.590
You can help these people.
I don't give a shit

28:38.592 --> 28:42.928
about helping people.
I give a shit about helping me,

28:42.930 --> 28:45.597
which is why I want $50,000.
What?

28:45.599 --> 28:47.866
I just told you--
you cost me millions.

28:47.868 --> 28:49.802
So if you want my help--
Okay, never mind.

28:49.804 --> 28:51.003
Mike, I knew this was
a bad idea.

28:51.005 --> 28:52.871
- We'll pay it.
- Mike.

28:52.873 --> 28:54.706
Rachel, if she can
get us something we can use,

28:54.708 --> 28:56.575
it's worth it.
It'll come out

28:56.577 --> 28:59.611
of the settlement offer.
Uh-uh, I want it up front.

28:59.613 --> 29:01.613
And how do we know that you
won't take the money and say

29:01.615 --> 29:03.882
that you couldn't find anything?
You don't,

29:03.884 --> 29:05.751
but, given the fact that
you're still here,

29:05.753 --> 29:07.786
it doesn't look like
you have much of a choice.

29:07.788 --> 29:10.556
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:10.558 --> 29:12.891
So how are you, Louis?

29:12.893 --> 29:14.660
Wanna know how I'm doing?
I'll tell you how I'm doing.

29:14.662 --> 29:16.728
I tried focusing on
my professional life

29:16.730 --> 29:19.598
instead of my personal one, and
it's been a goddamn disaster.

29:19.600 --> 29:20.966
I take it your thoughts
of Tara have been getting

29:20.968 --> 29:22.768
in the way of work.
What?

29:22.770 --> 29:24.937
No, I'm over her--
she's yesterday's news.

29:24.939 --> 29:26.772
Your words make me
think otherwise.

29:26.774 --> 29:28.640
Well, how about you listen
to these words:

29:28.642 --> 29:30.642
Harvey's making his friend
name partner.

29:30.644 --> 29:32.077
He's accused me of being
jealous, and I don't know

29:32.079 --> 29:33.846
what to do.
Are you jealous?

29:33.848 --> 29:36.882
Of course I'm goddamn jealous!

29:36.884 --> 29:39.985
Louis, it's natural for you
to feel that way.

29:39.987 --> 29:41.920
You've worked hard to get
where you are,

29:41.922 --> 29:44.823
and a new person threatens
your position in the firm.

29:44.825 --> 29:48.126
That's not--
That's just not it.

29:49.930 --> 29:53.565
The one silver lining
of Jessica leaving

29:53.567 --> 29:56.902
was that I thought that Harvey
would finally turn to me,

29:56.904 --> 30:01.573
not only as his partner,
but as his friend.

30:01.575 --> 30:04.843
That's not happening now
because I'm being replaced.

30:04.845 --> 30:09.181
And you're scared
of losing your friend.

30:09.183 --> 30:12.117
What do I do?

30:12.119 --> 30:14.720
I can't tell you that, Louis,

30:14.722 --> 30:17.789
but I can tell you
it was your behavior

30:17.791 --> 30:19.124
that drove Tara away,

30:19.126 --> 30:21.660
and, if you keep
letting your emotions

30:21.662 --> 30:23.128
dictate your behavior,

30:23.130 --> 30:26.965
you won't need to worry
about being replaced.

30:26.967 --> 30:30.035
You'll drive Harvey away
all by yourself.

30:30.037 --> 30:37.142
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:38.679 --> 30:41.713
I'm not sure I've ever
seen you here this late.

30:41.715 --> 30:45.851
New office, new hours.

30:45.853 --> 30:48.086
I guess so.

30:48.088 --> 30:50.822
Katrina, whatever's
on your mind,

30:50.824 --> 30:53.859
I recommend you just say it.

30:53.861 --> 30:57.129
As you know, I'm on track
to be a senior partner here.

30:57.131 --> 30:59.598
In fact, it's one of the main
reasons I agreed to come back.

30:59.600 --> 31:01.166
I know.

31:01.168 --> 31:03.001
I'm not saying Donna
doesn't deserve a promotion--

31:03.003 --> 31:06.838
I know what she does
as much as anyone.

31:06.840 --> 31:10.208
I'm just saying making partner
means something,

31:10.210 --> 31:15.147
and I'm concerned that being one
here won't mean what it used to.

31:15.149 --> 31:18.150
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:18.152 --> 31:20.752
What would you have me do?

31:20.754 --> 31:24.056
I don't know. I just thought,
if I was thinking it,

31:24.058 --> 31:26.191
it occurred to me
that others might be too,

31:26.193 --> 31:30.195
and I thought
you should know that.

31:30.197 --> 31:34.166
Katrina, being a partner here
will mean as much

31:34.168 --> 31:38.904
as it always has.
I'll make sure of it.

31:38.906 --> 31:46.011
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:52.153 --> 31:53.753
[knocking]

31:53.755 --> 31:56.623
I hope you came here
to tell me you got everything

31:56.625 --> 31:58.257
straightened out.
I came here to tell you

31:58.259 --> 32:02.328
that the deal's off the table.
What?

32:02.330 --> 32:06.099
Name partner means something,
and I can't just give it away

32:06.101 --> 32:08.167
to make a statement.
I never should've offered it

32:08.169 --> 32:10.269
to you in the first place.
God damn it, Harvey.

32:10.271 --> 32:12.372
This is the second time
you've done this.

32:12.374 --> 32:17.310
And I'm sorry, Alex, but this
is a take it or leave it offer.

32:17.312 --> 32:20.279
You can let me know
in the morning.

32:23.051 --> 32:25.151
I'll take it.

32:28.356 --> 32:32.258
I wasn't really gonna make
name partner in a year.

32:32.260 --> 32:35.094
Maybe not ever.

32:35.096 --> 32:37.030
I know.

32:37.032 --> 32:38.798
How?

32:38.800 --> 32:41.100
Because if they were really
gonna do it in a year,

32:41.102 --> 32:43.036
you would've leveraged them
to move it up the second

32:43.038 --> 32:44.437
I left your office.
So why didn't you

32:44.439 --> 32:47.173
call me on that before?
I don't know.

32:47.175 --> 32:49.108
Maybe it's because I felt
like I owe you,

32:49.110 --> 32:51.277
or maybe because I wanted
to prove to the world

32:51.279 --> 32:53.246
that I'm not Jessica.

32:53.248 --> 32:57.417
Or maybe it's because
I wanted to work together.

32:57.419 --> 32:59.419
I'll see you Monday, Harvey.

32:59.421 --> 33:01.421
See you Monday.

33:01.423 --> 33:06.292
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:06.294 --> 33:08.695
- I'll get that.
- Keep your money, Mr. Ross.

33:08.697 --> 33:10.430
You're gonna need it.

33:10.432 --> 33:12.198
I think, after you see this,
you're gonna wanna save

33:12.200 --> 33:15.768
every nickel you have.

33:15.770 --> 33:16.869
Thanks.

33:19.741 --> 33:22.208
Now, correct me if I'm wrong,
but I believe that's a memo

33:22.210 --> 33:25.445
between Acumen senior management
and their sales force

33:25.447 --> 33:28.247
outlining their policy
of doing whatever it takes

33:28.249 --> 33:29.782
to avoid paying claims.

33:29.784 --> 33:31.451
Well, this thing
can be interpreted

33:31.453 --> 33:33.319
a dozen different ways.
It doesn't prove a thing.

33:33.321 --> 33:34.821
But it proves that
we're not just talking

33:34.823 --> 33:36.322
about my client anymore.

33:36.324 --> 33:38.191
You're looking at
a class action.

33:38.193 --> 33:39.859
And if there's one thing that
a jury hates more

33:39.861 --> 33:41.828
than a fake lawyer,
it's an insurance company

33:41.830 --> 33:45.198
that rips off widowers
and children.

33:45.200 --> 33:47.467
- What do you want?
- 50 million.

33:47.469 --> 33:49.435
With an admission of guilt.
No way, they won't

33:49.437 --> 33:52.171
go for admission.
Okay, then here's what you're

33:52.173 --> 33:54.807
gonna do instead.

33:54.809 --> 33:56.809
A reporter's gonna call you.

33:56.811 --> 33:59.078
And when he does, you're gonna
tell him the story of how you

33:59.080 --> 34:01.114
thought you were gonna
wipe the floor

34:01.116 --> 34:04.083
with this fraudulent attorney,
but instead you ended up praying

34:04.085 --> 34:06.919
that you never
go up against him again.

34:06.921 --> 34:08.487
You knew they wouldn't
go for admission.

34:08.489 --> 34:11.224
You set me up.
Well, now that you mention it,

34:11.226 --> 34:14.226
I did.

34:14.228 --> 34:15.895
And that's take it or leave it.

34:15.897 --> 34:17.830
Then I guess I'll take it.

34:17.831 --> 34:20.266
And leave out the part where you
traded admission of guilt

34:20.268 --> 34:25.204
in exchange for self-promotion.
Don't you dare say that to me.

34:25.206 --> 34:27.507
I'm not doing this for myself.
I'm doing it so that

34:27.509 --> 34:30.909
pieces of shit like you
never try to use my history

34:30.911 --> 34:33.279
against my clients again.

34:33.281 --> 34:40.286
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:40.288 --> 34:42.355
Louis, before you
say anything...

34:42.357 --> 34:43.523
Harvey,
before you say anything,

34:43.525 --> 34:46.159
I just wanna say I'm sorry.

34:46.161 --> 34:48.960
You were right.
I was jealous

34:48.963 --> 34:51.931
of Alex coming over here,
but not because I'm afraid

34:51.933 --> 34:53.565
of another lawyer.
I don't understand.

34:53.568 --> 34:55.802
See, Harvey, I know you like
to make fun of me,

34:55.804 --> 34:58.938
and I know I might not
mean as much to you

34:58.940 --> 35:01.908
as you mean to me,
but you're my friend,

35:01.910 --> 35:04.310
and, because I don't have many,
that friendship

35:04.312 --> 35:05.978
is important to me.

35:05.980 --> 35:07.980
You don't have to worry
about that, Louis.

35:07.982 --> 35:11.517
But I don't want my behavior
to drive a wedge between us,

35:11.519 --> 35:16.355
which means I accept
Alex as name partner.

35:16.357 --> 35:18.224
- About that, Louis...
- I mean, it's just gonna

35:18.226 --> 35:21.227
have to be like when LeBron
James joined the Miami Heat

35:21.229 --> 35:23.596
when he and D-Wade
worked it out with Chris Bosh.

35:23.598 --> 35:26.332
I thought you didn't know
anything about sports.

35:26.334 --> 35:27.533
I stayed up all night
trying to come up with

35:27.535 --> 35:29.936
the right analogy.

35:29.938 --> 35:31.404
And, if I'm not mistaken,
they went on to win

35:31.406 --> 35:34.574
back-to-back Super Bowls.

35:34.576 --> 35:37.176
That they did.

35:37.178 --> 35:39.312
Louis, for what it's worth,
Alex is still coming,

35:39.314 --> 35:40.980
but not as name partner.
Really?

35:40.982 --> 35:43.983
Yeah, you were right.

35:43.985 --> 35:46.485
We can't water down
the firm like that.

35:46.487 --> 35:52.491
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:52.493 --> 35:54.060
[knocking]

35:55.496 --> 35:57.530
You've never knocked before.

35:57.532 --> 35:59.999
And you've never had
a door before.

36:00.001 --> 36:02.301
I know, and it's
a good thing I do because--

36:02.303 --> 36:03.870
You can't be a partner, Donna.

36:03.872 --> 36:06.405
What?

36:06.407 --> 36:07.640
You can't do that.

36:07.642 --> 36:09.342
I have to.
I made a mistake.

36:09.344 --> 36:12.945
Bullshit, I--
I paid you $500,000.

36:12.947 --> 36:15.248
You haven't signed
the partnership agreement yet,

36:15.250 --> 36:16.883
so I can refund your money,
and--

36:16.885 --> 36:18.951
I don't want a refund.
I want what we agreed to.

36:18.953 --> 36:20.953
I can't do that.

36:20.955 --> 36:24.624
You are not a lawyer, and
being partner at a law firm--

36:24.626 --> 36:29.028
it means something,
inside the firm and out,

36:29.030 --> 36:32.098
which is why I wrote up
a new release for you.

36:36.304 --> 36:38.237
This says
"Director of Personnel."

36:38.239 --> 36:39.939
Everybody knows
you're great with people,

36:39.941 --> 36:41.574
so it'll play out there,
but, between you and me--

36:41.576 --> 36:44.277
No, Harvey, I didn't ask
for partner just so I could

36:44.279 --> 36:46.512
keep being a superwoman
behind closed doors,

36:46.514 --> 36:49.448
but, to the rest of the world,
be a glorified office manager.

36:49.450 --> 36:53.619
Partner is off the table,
Donna.

36:53.621 --> 36:55.688
Then keep my buy-in
and make me COO.

36:55.690 --> 36:57.523
I can't do that--
that's the same as a partner.

36:57.525 --> 37:00.026
No, it isn't.
Skadden and Zane

37:00.028 --> 37:03.996
and Bratton Gould all have COOs,
and none of them are lawyers.

37:03.998 --> 37:05.531
How do you know that?

37:05.533 --> 37:06.933
'Cause I never thought
you'd make me partner

37:06.935 --> 37:08.668
in the first place.

37:11.673 --> 37:15.374
- Okay, it's a deal.
- And I keep my vote.

37:15.376 --> 37:16.976
- Donna--
- Within these walls,

37:16.978 --> 37:21.480
I have a seat at the table.
Take it or leave it.

37:21.482 --> 37:23.449
I'll take it.

37:23.451 --> 37:28.688
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:28.690 --> 37:31.123
Thanks, Harvey.

37:31.125 --> 37:33.592
You're gonna make
a hell of a COO.

37:33.594 --> 37:40.700
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:41.636 --> 37:44.570
And?
How'd it go?

37:44.572 --> 37:46.572
Out of the park.

37:46.574 --> 37:50.076
Got everything we wanted.

37:50.078 --> 37:53.546
What do you say we go out
and celebrate tonight?

37:53.548 --> 37:57.550
Well, we're celebrating,
but we're not going out.

37:57.552 --> 38:00.052
What do you mean?

38:00.054 --> 38:03.155
A reporter from "The Times" is
gonna be here in five minutes.

38:03.157 --> 38:07.159
- Okay.
- We are doing an interview.

38:07.161 --> 38:10.196
The redemption
of a fraudulent lawyer.

38:13.668 --> 38:16.335
Well, that is the best news
I've heard since finding out

38:16.337 --> 38:20.006
you got into the bar.
Thank you.

38:20.008 --> 38:22.041
But I think you should
do it without me.

38:22.043 --> 38:25.678
Rachel, I--I couldn't have
done any of this without you.

38:25.680 --> 38:28.047
And that may be true,
but this is your story,

38:28.049 --> 38:31.650
and you should be
the one to tell it.

38:34.722 --> 38:37.757
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:37.759 --> 38:42.595
Go--I'll see you at home.

38:42.597 --> 38:49.702
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:00.515 --> 39:02.148
- Mike?
- Yeah.

39:02.150 --> 39:04.216
- David Gruen.
- Good to meet you.

39:04.218 --> 39:05.618
Where do you want to do this?

39:05.620 --> 39:08.087
I was thinking maybe
your new office.

39:08.089 --> 39:10.489
Uh, yeah, we could
end up there.

39:10.491 --> 39:12.658
But I was thinking maybe we'd
start out where I started out.

39:12.660 --> 39:15.728
- Where's that?
- In the bullpen.

39:15.730 --> 39:22.735
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:22.737 --> 39:25.504
<i>[line trilling]</i>

39:25.506 --> 39:28.140
[phone buzzing]

39:28.142 --> 39:30.776
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:30.778 --> 39:32.745
What is it now, Harvey?

39:32.747 --> 39:35.114
<i>You want to put the janitor</i>
<i>in charge of bankruptcy?</i>

39:35.116 --> 39:38.818
Or the guard downstairs could be
head of litigation.

39:38.820 --> 39:41.687
- Are you finished?
- Depends on what you say next.

39:41.689 --> 39:43.656
I'm sorry I said
those things about you,

39:43.658 --> 39:47.159
and I want you to know
I didn't mean any of them.

39:47.161 --> 39:48.861
I'm sorry too, Harvey.

39:48.863 --> 39:50.863
Jessica, you don't
need to apologize.

39:50.865 --> 39:53.499
Yes, I do.

39:53.501 --> 39:56.669
You were just tearing
the statue down.

39:56.671 --> 39:59.505
Just like you saw me do
all those years ago,

39:59.507 --> 40:01.807
and I didn't like it

40:01.809 --> 40:03.843
because the statue was me.

40:03.845 --> 40:06.212
Well, if it's the same to you,

40:06.214 --> 40:08.681
I'd like the statue to stay.

40:08.683 --> 40:10.483
Sounds good to me.

40:10.485 --> 40:14.487
- There's one more thing.
<i>- There always is.</i>

40:14.489 --> 40:18.724
I'm still bringing Alex over,
only not as a name partner,

40:18.726 --> 40:22.862
but Pfizer's still insisting
we drop Jim Reynolds.

40:22.864 --> 40:25.531
And you want to know
if I'm okay with it?

40:25.533 --> 40:28.901
No, I'm letting him go.

40:28.903 --> 40:31.270
I'm just calling you to tell you
before I tell him,

40:31.272 --> 40:34.573
<i>like I should've done</i>
<i>in the first place.</i>

40:34.575 --> 40:37.610
I was wrong when I said
you weren't ready, Harvey.

40:37.612 --> 40:39.578
No, you weren't,

40:39.580 --> 40:41.213
but you are now.

40:41.215 --> 40:43.249
Good night, Closer.

40:43.251 --> 40:45.251
Good night, Jessica.

40:45.253 --> 40:47.553
<i>And take your feet</i>
<i>off my desk.</i>

40:47.555 --> 40:50.789
[chuckles] Not a chance.

40:50.791 --> 40:53.792
<i>[upbeat music]</i>

